]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"cce3c3",
"children":[
"Acute ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"mitral regurgitation",
"children":[
"MR"
]
},
" most often occurs in patients with chordae tendineae rupture. Characteristic findings include the abrupt onset of dyspnea, pulmonary edema, or cardiogenic shock. The murmur may be short or absent in patients with acute MR. A soft S",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"3"
]
},
" and P",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
" are usually heard."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"266a56",
"children":[
"Chronic mitral regurgitation is classified as primary, involving any portion of the mitral annulus, or secondary, involving causes other than the annulus (e.g., ventricular dysfunction)."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0efb2e",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"transthoracic echocardiography",
"children":[
"TTE"
]
},
" serves as the main imaging modality in the evaluation and management of MR."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s25_2",
